# home

Mac-first dotfiles and small home-bin utilities.

This repository started as a portable Linux/bash/vim home directory. The current
tracked setup now captures the intended macOS/zsh home configuration while
leaving older Linux desktop material in place for reference until it is
deliberately retired.

## Maintained Home Config

- `.zshrc` is the small base zsh source: path dedupe, generic helpers,
  history, and safe aliases/functions.
- `dotfiles/zshrc.d/` contains optional zsh templates for machine-specific
  sections such as workspaces, Pi/Pico, Zephyr, Ollama, nvm, Python, Docker,
  Postgres, Racket, Go, Keychain secrets, Brave, and zsh-tips-agent.
- `.gitconfig` is the maintained Git source for this machine.
- `.vimrc` is the historical Vim baseline and still belongs in the install set.

Install maintained dotfiles explicitly after review:

```sh
tools/install --dotfiles --prompt
```

Notable current choices:

- zsh deduplicates `PATH` with `typeset -U path PATH`.
- `~/.local/bin` is managed directly in `.zshrc`; the generated
  `~/.local/bin/env` helper is not needed in this repo.
- Machine-specific paths and selected zsh templates are loaded from
  `~/.config/home-repo/paths.zsh`.
- Optional zsh sections are not copied into the generated home `.zshrc` unless
  they were already selected, explicitly requested, set through the environment,
  or accepted during the installer prompt.
- `ls` aliases are macOS-first (`ls -G`) with GNU/Linux fallbacks.
- API secrets are loaded on demand from macOS Keychain with `setvar`; secret
  values must never be committed. Linux equivalents are Secret Service
  (`secret-tool`) for desktops or `pass` for headless systems.
- GitHub credentials are delegated to `gh`; non-GitHub credentials can use the
  macOS Keychain helper.
- Scheduled agent jobs use `AGENTIC_RUNTIME`, `AGENTIC_ONE_OFF_CMD`, and
  `OBSIDIAN_VAULT_DIR`. These are command/path settings, not secrets.
- Git fsmonitor is off globally. Large repositories can opt in locally with:

  ```sh
  git config --local core.fsmonitor true
  ```

## Repository Layout

- `install/bin/`: maintained command sources that this repo can install.
- `dotfiles/zshrc.d/`: optional zsh fragments injected into the generated
  `.zshrc` only when configured.
- `tools/`: repo-maintenance commands. These are not installed as home-bin
  commands.
- `tests/`: unit tests for maintained commands and repo tooling.
- `docs/`: usage notes for installable commands.
- `bin/`: historical legacy material from the original repo. It is not the
  source of truth for newly maintained commands.

## Installer

This repo no longer assumes it is checked out directly into `$HOME`.

Run:

```sh
tools/install --dry-run
```

By default, the installer installs user-level commands to `~/.local/bin`.
Privileged/shared commands are installed explicitly:

```sh
tools/install --user
tools/install --local
tools/install --all
tools/install --dotfiles
```

`--local` installs to `/usr/local/lib` and `/usr/local/bin` through `sudo`.
`--dotfiles` installs `.gitconfig` and `.vimrc` directly, and generates
`$HOME/.zshrc` from the base `.zshrc` plus selected templates in
`dotfiles/zshrc.d/`. Existing files are backed up first. With `--prompt`, it
asks for optional sections and writes chosen paths plus
`HOME_REPO_ZSH_TEMPLATES` to `~/.config/home-repo/paths.zsh`.

The prompt flow is grouped so dependent settings can be skipped together. For
example, if `PUB` is not configured, the installer asks once whether to
configure `GH`/`HF`; Pi/Pico, Zephyr, and scheduled agent/Obsidian settings use
the same blank-to-skip pattern.

To add one optional zsh section later without reworking the whole file:

```sh
make list-zsh-sections
make install-zsh-section ZSH_SECTION=nvm
```

Section names are the filenames under `dotfiles/zshrc.d/` without the `.zsh`
suffix.

Make targets are thin wrappers around the installer:

```sh
make install-user
make install-local
make install-all
make install-dotfiles
make list-zsh-sections
make install-zsh-section ZSH_SECTION=nvm
```

## Installable Keepers

The cleaned installable command sources are:

- `install/bin/sort_mypy.py`: sorts mypy-style diagnostic blocks by path and
  line.
- `install/bin/pr_capture.py`: captures GitHub pull request context into
  Markdown using the GitHub CLI.
- `install/bin/git-safestart`: installable as `git safestart`; prepares a repo
  and configured submodules before running the repo's default command.
- `install/bin/git-co`: installable as `git co`; checkout companion that reuses
  `git-safestart` without running the repo command.
- `install/bin/git-bump`: installable as `git bump`; triggers GitHub Actions
  workflow dispatches without no-op commits.
- `install/bin/zip_project`: creates a zip archive from tracked Git files plus
  unignored untracked files.
- `install/bin/git-purge-old-branches`: installable as
  `git purge-old-branches` and `git pob`; dry-runs or safely deletes old
  branches.
- `install/bin/brew-admin`: optional macOS role-account wrapper for Homebrew.
- `install/bin/obsidian-interlink-agent`: one scheduled agent pass to add
  Obsidian wikilinks between Markdown notes.
- `install/bin/setup-obsidian-interlink-cron`: idempotently installs the cron
  entry for the Obsidian interlink agent when the agent and vault exist.

Setup-oriented Make targets prompt for missing required values when the repo
does not already have a usable default. Blank answers skip that section for
later instead of writing broken config.

These are intentionally skipped:

- `set-image-location`: writes GPS metadata to images using the current public
  IP location.
- `uv`, `uvx`, Python symlinks, `aider`, and `og`: installer-managed tools, not
  repo-owned scripts.
- `gh_find_stale_forks.sh`: destructive archive/delete helper that needs a
  report-first rewrite before it belongs in shared dotfiles.

## Legacy Material

The original Conky/Ruby/bash files remain in the repo for now. They are not part
of the active macOS home setup. In particular, `bin/lib/conky/github.cog` uses
old GitHub password-era patterns and should not be carried forward without a
rewrite.

## Verification

Run:

```sh
tools/verify
```

The verifier checks:

- `.zshrc` syntax
- optional zsh template syntax and an all-templates generated parse check
- executable bash scripts in `install/bin/` and `tools/`
- Python syntax for installable Python scripts and tests
- unit tests
- high-confidence token/private-key patterns

This scan is intentionally conservative. It catches obvious secret values, but a
human review is still required before committing changes to public dotfiles.
